1 Introduction

This notebook describes the analyses presented in the paper: Al-Tamimi, J. (under review). Acoustic correlates of an epilaryngeal constriction in Levantine Arabic Guttural consonants. Interpseech 2019, Graz - Austria.

3 Description of the dataset

This data is obtained from ten speakers producing various consonants in the frame VCV, with V = symmetric /i: a: u:/ (=vowel) and C is one of 22 consonants put into six categories: “plain”, “velar”, “uvular”, “pharyngealised”, “pharyngeal” and glottal (=context). The data is from audio recordings synchronised with ultrasound tongue imaging, and electroglottography (with larynx constriction and height). For the current acoustic data, we have obtained voice quality measures and formant frequencies from the software VoiceSauce by using the parameters from Praat (for f0 and formant estimation). The current analyses are on voice quality metrics. After obtaining the data from VoiceSauce, manual data verification took place by visualising a spectrogram and looking at the patterns in the data. Formant frequencies were adapted to each speaker and vowel context (for the back vowel /u:/, we used another set of formant ceiling). F0 data were speaker adapted by estimating the range of each speaker before applying data extraction.

Once the data was verified, we obtained 11 points of measurements in each of the vowels preceding and following (V1 and V2 respectively) the consonant of interest. Below we present the data for each of V1 and V2.

A total of 66 words (=word) were obtained and these were repeated 3 times. The outcome is each acoustic measure, and the predictors are context and vowel, and the random factors are speaker and word. We also evaluate (at a later stage) the role of the sex of the speaker in evaluating differences.

4.2.3 Central imputation

Some of the variables in the dataset are empty (total is less than 10). To allow us using Random Forests in an appropriate way, we cannot have empty cases. We use the package DMwR for central imputations of the missing data.

# Central imputation using the package "DMwR".
dfPharRFSubV2[, 16:549] <- centralImputation(dfPharRFSubV2[, 16:549])

4.2.4 Z-scoring of the data

The data we have here comes from a variety of correlates that differ in their scales. To allow for a meaningful interpretation of the results, we z-score the data to put all predictors on the same level

# from the package "dplyr"
# V2
all_z <- select(dfPharRFSubV2, H1c_01:A2mnA3_01)
all_z <- cbind(all_z, select(dfPharRFSubV2))
all_z <- apply(all_z, 2, scale)
colnames(all_z) <- paste(colnames(all_z), 'z', sep = '_')
dfPharRFSubV2 <- cbind(dfPharRFSubV2, all_z)

5 Linear Mixed effects Modelling

We use Linear Mixed effects Modelling in a confirmatory way to evaluate the differences between the 6 contexts with respect to each of the predictors. We will look at five predictors only that were reported in the paper. The remaining data will be evaluated further in a future publication

5.1 Z2-Z1

5.1.1 Model Specification

5.1.1.1 Full Model

mdl.V2Z2Z1.Full <- lmer(Z2mnZ1_01~context+vowel+Sex+(context+vowel||Speaker)+
                          (1|targetWord),data=dfPharRFSubV2,
                        control = lmerControl(optimizer = "bobyqa",optCtrl=list(maxfun=1e5)))

5.1.1.2 Null Model

mdl.V2Z2Z1.Null <- lmer(Z2mnZ1_01~vowel+Sex+(vowel||Speaker)+
                          (1|targetWord),data=dfPharRFSubV2,
                        control = lmerControl(optimizer = "bobyqa",optCtrl=list(maxfun=1e5)))

7 Random Forest

7.1 Description

The patterns observed above show differences between the specific four categories: Plain, Uvular, Pharyngeal and Pharygealised as well as Velar and Glottal. We use Random Forests as a classification tool to evaluate the robustness of the observed differences and as a way to eliminate some of the correlates that do not contribute to the differences. We will grow several Random Forests as follows:

  1. One Forest on V2 Onset with the six contexts. We will add the vowel specification to the 21 predictors

  2. Another Forest similar to the first one but while adding the consonant ID as a way to increase the interactions within the dataframe. This will allow the forest to assign appropriate predictions to categories.

7.2 Creating training and testing datasets

# creating training and testing sets
# we set the seeds for reproducibility
# for V2
set.seed(1)
train.idx <- sample(nrow(dfPharRFSubV2), 2/3 * nrow(dfPharRFSubV2))
PharV2.train <- dfPharRFSubV2[train.idx, ]
PharV2.test <- dfPharRFSubV2[-train.idx, ]

7.3 Model 1:

7.3.1 Model specification

set.seed(1)
cforestPharV2.O.NoCons.train <- cforest(context~vowel+
                                 CPP_01_z+Energy_01_z+
                                 H1A1c_01_z+
                                 H1A2c_01_z+
                                 H1A3c_01_z+H1H2c_01_z+
                                 H2H4c_01_z+
                                 H2KH5Kc_01_z+
                                 H42Kc_01_z+HNR05_01_z+
                                 HNR15_01_z+
                                 HNR25_01_z+HNR35_01_z+SHR_01_z+
                                  soe_01_z+
                                 Z1mnZ0_01_z+Z2mnZ1_01_z+
                                   Z3mnZ2_01_z+A1mnA2_01_z+
                                   A1mnA3_01_z+A2mnA3_01_z, 
                                       data = PharV2.train, control=cforest_unbiased(mtry=round(sqrt(23)),ntree=500))
# we use predict to obtain predictions from the training set on the testing set
cforestPharV2.O.NoCons.Test <- predict(cforestPharV2.O.NoCons.train, newdata = PharV2.test, OOB=TRUE, type = "response")
